Nowhere is that density clearer than in the fight over representation. In Texas, Republican leaders, acting at Donald Trump\'92s urging, open a mid\uc0\u8209 decade redistricting process designed to turn five Democratic\u8209 leaning congressional seats into Republican ones. Texas House Democrats respond with the most powerful tool left to a minority in a majoritarian chamber: they leave the state, denying a quorum and halting the map. Their flight to Illinois and other states is not a symbolic gesture. It is a bid to keep the existing districts in place long enough to force negotiation or litigation. In a healthy system, such a standoff would remain a political struggle inside the legislature. Here, it is quickly recast as a matter for police, courts, and even federal law enforcement. That is the turn.\
\
Governor Greg Abbott and Attorney General Ken Paxton threaten the absent Democrats with fines, removal from office, and even felony charges for accepting flights and lodging from supporters. The legislature authorizes $500 daily fines for each day they do not appear. Civil arrest warrants are issued, first within Texas and then, in a striking escalation, filed in Illinois with a request that they be honored under full faith and credit. Senator John Cornyn asks the FBI to help locate and arrest the lawmakers, and FBI Director Kash Patel reportedly agrees to assist. At the same time, Abbott petitions the Texas supreme court to declare at least one Democratic seat vacant. Law, in this sequence, is not a neutral frame for resolving a dispute; it is a set of tools deployed to break the resistance of a political minority and clear the way for a map that will lock in majority power for years. The message is plain.\
