Indiana becomes the next front in the same campaign. Vice President J.D. Vance travels to meet with Republican legislators and encourage them to redraw their own congressional map to squeeze out additional Democratic seats, even though Republicans already hold seven of nine. Protesters gather at the Statehouse to denounce the plan, and some Republicans in Washington, like Representative Kevin Kiley and Representative Blake Moore, voice public unease with mid\uc0\u8209 decade gerrymanders. Kiley introduces a bill to ban such redistricting nationwide. But the weight of institutional power runs the other way. The vice president\'92s visit signals that the White House sees map\u8209 drawing as a national project, not a local one. The combination of Texas and Indiana shows how legislatures are being turned from arenas of representation into instruments for entrenchment, with law enforcement and federal power standing ready to discipline those who resist.\
